<p id="Par21" class="p">Cost frequency data are partitioned into slices, 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">i</italic>+1
 </sub>−
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">i</italic>
 </sub> = 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">S</italic>
 </sub>, where 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">S</italic>
 </sub> is one billion (adjusted to 2014 USD). Three aggregate slices were also created, 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">L</italic>
 </sub> &lt; 4 × 10
 <sup class="sup">9</sup>
 <italic class="italic">USD</italic>, 
 <inline-formula id="IEq1" class="inline-formula">
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M5" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$4\le {C}_{M} &lt; 11\times {10}^{9}\,USD$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M6" class="math">
    <mn class="mn">4</mn>
    <mo class="mo">≤</mo>
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">C</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">M</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">&lt;</mo>
    <mn class="mn">11</mn>
    <mo class="mo">×</mo>
    <msup class="msup">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">10</mn>
     </mrow>
     <mn class="mn">9</mn>
    </msup>
    <mspace width=".25em" class="mspace"/>
    <mi class="mi">U</mi>
    <mi class="mi">S</mi>
    <mi class="mi">D</mi>
   </math>
   <inline-graphic xlink:href="41598_2018_29680_Article_IEq1.gif" class="inline-graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </inline-formula>, and 
 <inline-formula id="IEq2" class="inline-formula">
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M7" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$${C}_{H} &gt; 11\times {10}^{9}$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M8" class="math">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">C</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">H</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">&gt;</mo>
    <mn class="mn">11</mn>
    <mo class="mo">×</mo>
    <msup class="msup">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">10</mn>
     </mrow>
     <mn class="mn">9</mn>
    </msup>
   </math>
   <inline-graphic xlink:href="41598_2018_29680_Article_IEq2.gif" class="inline-graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </inline-formula> USD (2014 adjusted). The distributions of delays for these aggregate slices are given along with the accumulative data in Fig. 
 <xref rid="Fig5" ref-type="fig" class="xref">5</xref>. Despite the overall shapes, anthropogenic distributions have much larger statistics in the 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">H</italic>
 </sub> slice than do the natural events. The aggregated cuts, 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">L</italic>
 </sub>, 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">M</italic>
 </sub> and 
 <italic class="italic">C</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">H</italic>
 </sub>, resulted in mean delays that increase with increasing cost slice 
 <italic class="italic">i</italic>.
</p>
